	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Wizardry Essentials</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:dreamer3_9@msn.com">Faelweanlz</a> | 
		            10/25/2001 1:39:51 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">This guide is for the untwinked  wizard.   As most of it wont apply to those of you with the nice robes ubber daggers and staves. <BR>
<BR>
First and foremost, being a wizard is challenging.  You do not get forage or summon food or healing spells to recover from that gawd awful beating you just took at the hands of that pesky beast.  <BR>
<BR>
I will skip 1-4 as it is all the same for all classes.  You will be doing a lot of tanking in the beginning.  Wizards are not in demand at low levels because you&#8217;re a terrible tank and your spells are terrible compared to the magician and enchanter (they get those nice pets) That changes somewhat at level 8 when you get much nicer DD spells.  This is when a lot of people figure out that they really wanted to be a magician.  I have both my piercing skill and my 1hb skill up  nicely.  I prefer the 1hb frankly because the staff does more damage.   While you will never be an effective tank its critical that you max out your melee skill level to insure that you are raising your DEFENSIVE skill.  This can buy you that extra amount of life that allows you to make it to the zone or guards.<BR>
<BR>
 Do NOT under estimate the importance of maxing out your 1HB and Piercing skills they will also effect your offensive and defensive skills.  Trust me&#8230; When that dumb green Orc centurion decides to attack you really don&#8217;t want to have to waste a lot of manna killing it.   Run EARLY and Run often is the motto of the young wizard who wishes to avoid running from his death spawn site to C/R.   <BR>
<BR>
If your untwinked and broke (somehow those conditions go hand in hand) then you will have to spend time working your way up.  On the plus side, you&#8217;ll know your characters strengths and weaknesses better and probably have better skills at lower and mid levels as it will take you longer to level.  People will tell you that you can just gather up lots of CB belts and Pads and sell them like hot cakes&#8230; Bull !  While it is true that you can occasionally sell them there isn&#8217;t a large market for them.   I for one am more interested in playing the game than waiting 45 minutes until someone wants to buy a bunch of belts and or pads.  Play the game the loot will come. You will have to make due with the standard issue equipment.   I have been playing for quite a while ( over 2 years ) and the key to getting help is really very simple.  Be NICE, Be Polite.  Remember they do not have to give you anything.  So if they don&#8217;t answer you it means no.    95% of the time people are willing to respond to polite, private requests.   That Druid doesn&#8217;t owe you a Sow or a Skin like ____.  The enchanter has no responsibility to Breeze or Clarity you. <BR>
<BR>
Level 8 to 12;  I am currently in Crushbone hunting Orc Centurions.  You will quickly find that the green orcs that shortly ago were blue still hit just as hard (IE they can kill you) and the legionnaire&#8217;s  simply beat you to a pulp if your root doesn&#8217;t hold.  This means group time.  Fortunately, your peer&#8217;s are starting to quickly recognize that the wizard is a great ally in a group as he can quickly do massive damage with your Ice and Fire bolt.  And your AOE are simply indispensable when more mob&#8217;s attack than the group wants.  I am currently  a level 9 and was (very shortly) in a group of 13 &#8211; 15 (the 15 was too high for me to get exp. so I left after this happened) but the group got attacked by 2 Lego&#8217;s and an Emissary and 2 Cents.  I was casing my lowly level 8 AOE and did a LOT of damage to all of the mob.  After the fight was over all critters killed and all party members alive they were asking &#8220;Who was casting?&#8221;  Don&#8217;t let anyone sell you short on the value the Wizard can play in a well run group.<BR>
<BR>
Is playing a wizard difficult?  You bet it is.  But there are few of us (in comparison to the 9 gazillion wood elf druids and rangers) or the 10 trillion dwarf clerics&#8230; In reality if you play your wizard well getting into groups should be as difficult as many would have you think.  We are dependent on the group for survival, but many a group will acknowledge that the group was dependent on survival because of the wizard.  <BR>
<BR>
So if you&#8217;re an untwinked wizard the challenge is great but the rewards really will roll in later in life.  Forget the riches offered by the get quick rich crowd, focus on max&#8217;ing your skills and when you are in your 20&#8217;s and 30&#8217;s you will have the money AND the skill to be an effective wizard.<BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
